OSTEICHTHYES (bony fish)	:	ACANTHOMORPHA INCERTAE SEDIS (thorn-shaped fish)	ACIPENSERIFORMES (ray-finned bony fish)	"ALEPISAURIFORMES (""lizard form without scales"")"	"AMIIFORMES (primitive ray-finned fish, very long dorsal fin)"	ANGUILLIFORMES (true eels)	"ATHERINIFORMES (ray-finned fish, silvery in colour)"	"AULOPIFORMES (deep-sea ray-finned fish, some can self-fertilise)"	BATRACHOIDIFORMES (toadfish)	BELONIFORMES (streamlined fish that live close to the surface of water; includes flying fish)	BERYCIFORMES (ray-finned fish)	BOBASATRANIFORMES	CEPHALOXENIFORMES (thick head bones and crushing dentition)	CLUPEIFORMES (ray-finned fish including herrings and anchovies)	"COELOCANTHIFORMES  (=Crossopterygii, lobe-finned fish, armour-like scales)"	"CROSSOGNATHIFORMES (bony, ray-finned fish)"	"CTENOTHRISSIFORMES (teleostean fish, link between soft-rayed and spiny-rayed fish)"	DACTYLOPTERIFORMES (greatly enlarged pectoral fins that resemble wings)	"DIPTERIFORMES (= Dipnoi, lungfish, can breathe air)"	ELOPIFORMES (single dorsal fin with only soft rays)	GADIFORMES (cods & hakes)	"GASTEROSTEIFORMES (ray-finned fish that includes sea horses, pipefishes, and sticklebacks)"	GONORHYNCHIFORMES (ray-finned fish with small mouths and no teeth)	"LAMPRIDIFORMES (deep sea ray-finned fish, highly protrusible jaws, lack fin spines and scales, typically brightly coloured)"	LOPHIIFORMES (anglerfish)	MACROSEMIIFORMES (teleost ray-finned fish)	MEGALOPIFORMES	MYCTOPHIFORMES (small fish with subterminal mouths with numerous tiny teeth and light-producing organs)	"OPHIDIIFORMES (ray-finned fish that resemble eels, have long dorsal fins and an anal fin)"	OSMERIFORMES (generally silvery and elongate fish)	"OSTEOGLOSSIFORMES (mostly f/w, toothed or bony tongues)"	PACHYCORMIFORMES (ray-finned fish with serrated pectoral fins)	PALAEONISCIFORMES (earliest known and most primitive ray-finned forms)	PELTOPLEURIFORMES	PERCIFORMES (bony ray-finned fish with dorsal and anal fins divided into anterior spiny and posterior soft-rayed portions)	"PERLEIDIFORMES (bony, diamond-shaped, not-overlaping scales)"	"PHOLIDOPLEURIFORMES (crushing dentition, long and slender, anal fins far back on the body)"	"PLEURONECTIFORMES (flatfish, often with both eyes in one side of the head)"	POLYMIXIIFORMES (deep-sea marine ray-finned fish with a pair of long hyoid barbels)	PTYCHOLEPIFORMES (spindle-like shape that is wide in the middle and tapes at both ends)	PYCNODONTIFORMES (ray-finned bony fish)	"SALMONIFORMES (ray-finned fish including salmon, trout, with pelvic fins far back and having a forked tail)"	SAURICHTHYIFORMES (vertical jaw-support)	"SCORPAENIFORMES
